    <title>Combined summary - [BIP Proposal] Version bits with timeout and delay.</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T22:25:48.638737+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-September/010998.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In September 2015, discussions were held on the bitcoin-dev mailing list regarding the implementation of a new consensus rule in Bitcoin protocol. The proposed rule required miners to set a bit in the block header for blocks larger than 1MB in size, and if more than 75% of the blocks within a window of 2016 have the bit set, then reject all blocks that have the bit set and fail to meet the rule. However, Jorge Timon pointed out that until it becomes a consensus rule, nodes may not follow the standard policy of applying the restrictions at 75% and could apply them at 0% or 90%.The email thread between Tier Nolan and Jorge Timón discussed the best approach to implementing the new rule. Nolan suggested that if 75% of blocks in the last 2016 window have the bit set, then all blocks that do not meet the new rule should be rejected. Timón argued that relying on nodes to follow the standard policy is not enough and suggested instead applying the new rule from the start in their own blocks and waiting for 95% consensus activation. Nolan asked for the advantages and disadvantages of each approach.A proposed change to the semantics of the 'version' field in Bitcoin blocks is specified in a document, allowing multiple backward-compatible changes to be deployed in parallel by interpreting the version field as a bit vector. A discussion on activation mechanisms for old soft/hardforks is ongoing, with some suggesting that height may replace the mechanism in the future. The proposed Version bits with timeout and delay is a change to the semantics of Bitcoin blocks' version field, allowing multiple backward-compatible changes (soft forks) to be deployed in parallel. In a discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list in September 2015, Rusty Russell proposes that the consensus rules related to 'locked-in' soft fork will be enforced in the second retarget period. This means that there is one retarget period in which the remaining 5% can upgrade. After the activation block and onwards, bit B may be reused for a different soft fork.A proposal has been made to enforce a new rule at 75% of mining majority, but only for blocks with the bit set. The advantage of doing this is that miners will receive early notification if they have implemented the rule incorrectly. There are three possible failures, but the proposal is designed so that miners always get about two weeks' warning before those drop to SPV security. In conclusion, Rusty is not convinced by the extra complexity.The discussions cover topics such as the use of height versus time as a measure of deployment speed, the association of states with softfork proposals, the usefulness of a soft fork and partial enforcement, and the importance of ensuring all nodes on the network are compliant. There are debates over whether to wait for 75% consensus before enforcing new restrictions on one's own blocks or to enforce the restrictions from the start, and waiting for 95% consensus activation. In addition, Rusty Russell suggested that a timeout is needed for ancient nodes that cannot be detected if they fork themselves off the network due to a failed BIP bit. The conversation also touches on the activation mechanism in Bitcoin and whether to use height or time to replace it. It is agreed upon that setting the restriction at 95% would be safer as it will produce fewer orphaned blocks. However, implementing restrictions in one's own block can be done at 0%. The conversation also touches on using height versus time for bip writers and the ease of writing "block x" versus "date y". Finally, in an email exchange between Rusty Russell and Tom Harding regarding the consensus rules related to a locked-in soft fork, concerns are raised about support falling off during a delay period for a new proposal. However, both agree that adding more complexity for a situation that is unlikely to happen is a mistake. The BIP was changed to allow for visibility on any fall off in support, though no action would be taken to address it.The discussions highlight the importance of achieving consensus among bitcoin users when making changes to the network.</summary>
